# Lazy Evaluation of Expensive Functions in OR/CASE

## Description

Reorders OR predicates and CASE branches so cheap conditions are
evaluated first, short-circuiting before expensive functions run.
In `expensive_f(x) OR cheap_check`, swap to `cheap_check OR expensive_f(x)`.

**When to apply**: OR/CASE with a mix of cheap and expensive conditions
where evaluation order can be changed without semantic difference.

**Why it works**: SQL OR short-circuits (in most implementations).
Evaluating the cheap branch first means the expensive branch is
skipped when the cheap branch is true.

## Implementation

```rust
rw!("reorder-or-cheap-first";
    "(or ?expensive ?cheap)" => "(or ?cheap ?expensive)"
    if is_expensive("?expensive") && !is_expensive("?cheap")
),
rw!("reorder-case-cheap-first";
    "(case (when ?expensive_cond ?then1) (when ?cheap_cond ?then2) ?rest)" =>
    "(case (when ?cheap_cond ?then2) (when ?expensive_cond ?then1) ?rest)"
    if is_expensive("?expensive_cond") && !is_expensive("?cheap_cond") &&
       branches_independent("?expensive_cond", "?cheap_cond")
),
```

## Preconditions

Branches must be independent (neither depends on the other). If
branch evaluation has side effects, reordering is not safe.

## Test Cases

### Positive: Cheap check before regex

```sql
WHERE REGEXP_MATCH(content, 'complex.*pattern') OR status = 'flagged'
-- Reorder: WHERE status = 'flagged' OR REGEXP_MATCH(content, ...)
```

### Negative: Dependent conditions

```sql
WHERE x IS NOT NULL AND expensive_f(x) > 0
-- Cannot reorder: second branch depends on first (NULL guard)
```

